<section class="block" id="work">
  <div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow reveal"><span class="dot"></span>Day job</p>
    <h2 class="reveal">Reading the brain, honestly</h2>
    <p class="lede reveal">
      The signals are small, the noise is large, and the interesting part is everything you do
      before the statistics. I'm the engineer here, not the neuroscientist — this is what I
      spend my days on.
    </p>
    <div class="cards">
      <article class="card reveal">
        <span class="stripe" style="background:var(--hbo)"></span>
        <span class="tag t-hbo">fNIRS</span>
        <h3>Preprocessing that survives review</h3>
        <p>
          Optical density → motion correction (TDDR, wavelet, spline) → modified Beer–Lambert →
          HbO/HbR, with short-separation channels regressing out systemic noise. Reproducible,
          documented, and boring in the best way.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card reveal">
        <span class="stripe" style="background:var(--blue)"></span>
        <span class="tag t-blue">Montage</span>
        <h3>Optode layouts under constraints</h3>
        <p>
          Choosing source–detector placements that maximize cortical sensitivity to the regions
          that matter — while physically sharing the cap with EEG electrodes. A
          coverage-vs-constraints optimization, not a guess.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card reveal">
        <span class="stripe" style="background:var(--mint)"></span>
        <span class="tag t-mint">EEG</span>
        <h3>Two modalities, one head</h3>
        <p>
          Co-registering electrical and hemodynamic signals so they explain each other instead
          of fighting for scalp real estate.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
